      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The leak occurs because `processOrder` only takes ownership of the `Order*` but never returns or stores it for later cleanup, so the raw pointer is left dangling when the function exits. You can fix this by wrapping the pointer in a smart pointer (e.g., `std::unique_ptr`) and returning it from the function, then using that return value in the caller.\n\nHere’s a minimal fix:\n\n```cpp\n#include <memory>\n\nvoid processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> order) {\n    if (order->isValid()) {\n        executeTrade(order);\n    }\n    // No manual delete needed – unique_ptr cleans up automatically\n}\n\n// elsewhere in the code\nauto myOrder = std::make_unique<Order>(1234);\nprocessOrder(std::move(myOrder));\n```\n\n**Why it works**\n\n- `std::unique_ptr` owns the dynamically allocated `Order` and will free it when it goes out of scope.\n- By passing the pointer by value (and moving it into the function), the ownership is transferred to `processOrder`.\n- The function now *owns* the order, so the memory is released automatically when `processOrder`",
